    "review": {
      "summary": "The verb 'to be' (am/is/are) is used to describe identity, state, or condition. It changes form based on the subject: I am, he/she/it is, you/we/they are. Negatives add 'not' after the verb. Questions invert the verb and subject. Contractions are common in spoken English.",
      "summary_arabic": "يستخدم فعل 'يكون' (am/is/are) لوصف الهوية أو الحالة أو الشرط. يتغير شكله حسب الفاعل: I am، he/she/it is، you/we/they are. تضيف النفي 'not' بعد الفعل. تقلب الأسئلة الفعل والفاعل. الاختصارات شائعة في الإنجليزية المحكية.",
      "key_formulas": [
        {
          "formula": "Subject + am/is/are + complement",
          "example": "I am a student."
        },
        {
          "formula": "Subject + am/is/are + not + complement",
          "example": "She is not tired."
        },
        {
          "formula": "Am/Is/Are + subject + complement?",
          "example": "Are you ready?"
        },
        {
          "formula": "Question word + am/is/are + subject?",
          "example": "Where are you from?"
        }
      ],
      "quick_tips": [
        "I -> am always",
        "He/She/It -> is always",
        "You/We/They -> are always",
        "Not goes AFTER am/is/are",
        "In questions, am/is/are comes FIRST",
        "Use a/an before singular countable nouns"
      ]
    },
